    <h2 class="section-title">Four tiers, all enforced by Fire Marshal.</h2>

    <table class="price-table">
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Cooking volume</th><th>Cleaning frequency</th><th>Examples</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Solid-fuel</td><td>Monthly minimum</td><td>Wood-fired pizza, charcoal grill, BBQ smokehouse</td></tr>
        <tr><td>High-volume</td><td>Quarterly minimum</td><td>24-hour operations, char-grilling steakhouses, wok-heavy Asian, large hotel banquet</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Moderate-volume</td><td>Semi-annual minimum</td><td>Most restaurants, cafés, fast casual, brewery kitchens</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Low-volume</td><td>Annual minimum</td><td>Churches, seasonal kitchens, day camps, employee cafeterias</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <p>Fire Marshal enforces these schedules during routine inspection. Failure to maintain the schedule is a violation that can result in business closure until corrected. Documentation matters: the inspector wants to see the certificate from the most recent cleaning service, dated within the required interval.</p>

    <p>We document every cleaning service with a Fire Marshal compliance certificate that includes:</p>

    <ul class="bullet-list">
      <li><strong>Service date and operator name.</strong></li>
      <li><strong>Hood configuration and exhaust system identification.</strong></li>
      <li><strong>Pre-service grease accumulation level.</strong></li>
      <li><strong>Cleaning method and chemicals used.</strong></li>
      <li><strong>Post-service inspection notes.</strong></li>
      <li><strong>Our BHGS license number and C-20 HVAC scope reference.</strong></li>
      <li><strong>Next required service date.</strong></li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 03 HOT PRESSURE WASH SERVICE -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">03 · Hot pressure wash service procedure</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What's included in a full NFPA 96 cleaning visit.</h2>

    <ol class="ordered-list">
      <li><strong>Pre-cleaning preparation.</strong> Cover cooking surfaces, electronics, and any moisture-sensitive equipment. Drape exhaust path access points with collection sheeting to capture runoff.</li>
      <li><strong>Filter removal and bath.</strong> Remove all baffle filters; soak in hot degreaser bath; pressure-wash individually with 180°F+ water at 1,500+ PSI.</li>
      <li><strong>Hood plenum interior.</strong> Pressure-wash the interior plenum surfaces with hot degreaser, working from the front of the hood back toward the duct collar.</li>
      <li><strong>Accessible exhaust duct runs.</strong> Pressure-wash duct runs from access doors and inspection ports. Vertical risers and horizontal runs accessed at every panel point.</li>
      <li><strong>Fan housing and rooftop fan unit.</strong> Pressure-wash the fan housing interior, impeller blades (if accessible), and the rooftop fan curb. Rooftop access required; lift equipment if not on accessible roof.</li>
      <li><strong>Fan amp test and airflow measurement.</strong> Post-cleaning, verify fan amp draw is within nameplate (clean unit pulls less amps) and CFM at the rooftop is at code spec.</li>
      <li><strong>Filter reinstallation and visual inspection.</strong> Reinstall cleaned baffle filters; inspect welds and joint integrity; flag any damage for follow-up replacement.</li>
      <li><strong>Compliance certificate generation.</strong> Document service for Fire Marshal records.</li>
    </ol>

    <p>Service duration 3 to 6 hours typical for an 8-foot single-hood installation; multi-hood operations and complex rooftop access run longer. Most operations schedule cleaning during overnight downtime to avoid kitchen disruption.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 04 BAFFLE FILTER -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">04 · Baffle filter cleaning vs replacement</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">When cleaning is enough, when replacement is needed.</h2>

    <p>Baffle filters are stainless steel mesh assemblies that catch grease aerosol as exhaust passes through. They are designed for repeated cleaning and last many years if maintained properly. We make the cleaning-vs-replacement call based on physical condition.</p>

    <p><strong>Cleaning is sufficient when:</strong></p>

    <ul class="bullet-list">
      <li>Baffles are straight and undamaged.</li>
      <li>Welds and joints are intact.</li>
      <li>Mesh is unbroken and not deformed.</li>
      <li>Frame is square and seats properly in the filter rail.</li>
    </ul>

    <p><strong>Replacement is needed when:</strong></p>

    <ul class="bullet-list">
      <li>Baffles are warped from heat exposure or pressure washing.</li>
      <li>Welds are broken or pulling apart.</li>
      <li>Mesh has tears or holes that allow grease bypass.</li>
      <li>Frame is bent and no longer seats correctly.</li>
      <li>Stainless surface is severely corroded or pitted.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>Mid-tier baffle filter replacement $80 to $180 per filter (CaptiveAire 5400, Greenheck standard, generic stainless). Pro-tier filters $180 to $340 per filter (Halton, Vent Master, premium CaptiveAire models with specialty mesh patterns).</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 05 LA HARD WATER -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">05 · LA hard water and water-wash systems</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Mineral spotting and scale prevention.</h2>

    <p>LA-region hard water creates two issues during hood cleaning service:</p>

    <ul class="bullet-list">
      <li><strong>Mineral spotting on stainless after pressure wash.</strong> LADWP at 5 to 9 grains per gallon, MWD blends 7 to 12 grains, Calleguas (Ventura) 8 to 14 grains. Pressure-wash water leaves visible white mineral deposits when it dries on stainless surfaces. We use deionized water rinse on premium-tier installations (Halton, Vent Master, high-end CaptiveAire) to prevent spotting.</li>
      <li><strong>Scale on water-wash hood systems.</strong> Vent Master and Gaylord water-wash hoods rely on internal spray manifolds. Hard water scales the spray nozzles and clogs the detergent dispensing path. Routine descale included in annual contracts on these systems.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>Operators in inland LA County, Ventura County, and Inland Empire see hard water effects most. Coastal water (Santa Margarita Water District, parts of LA County coastal mix) is softer and produces less spotting.</p>
  </div>
</section>

